title: For Sale:  1952 Colt Light Weight Commander 38super/9mm
postcontent:
I have a 1952 Light Weight Commander. Prior to the steel framed Commander (also known as the combat commander) the Commander was only offered as a "light weight" alloy commander, while technically since it was the only Commander it was just called the "Commander". 

The pistol has the original grips (plastic/rubber material with colt Logo) as well as current Colt Commander wood grips (no logo). The current grips were taken off a 2012 Colt Steel Commander.

This Commander has holster wear, has moderate frame to slide wear with the oh so common colt "rattle". There are no cracks, no dings, and no problems with this Commander. I have shot over 200 rounds of 38 super and 200 rounds of 9mm. I have a high powered spring (new) set up for 38 super, as well as a new firing pin spring. This has been my carry gun for the last few months. In 9mm the spring that came with the pistol works (although I do not know the weight). I have not tried the high powered Wolff spring with 9mm, but suspect it is far to heavy. 

The pistol comes with both a 38 super barrel and bushing as well as 9mm barrel and bushing. Unknown manufacture of the barrels, but the 38 super is a "new" style and you will not have any of the common 38 super accuracy or extraction issues that 38 super barrels pre 1970s had.

I have one original 38 super COLT mag that works fine, although the spring may need a changing. I have a 9mm marked mag that fits 38 super, I have a dedicated newer 9mm mag. If you don't already know, 38 mags will take 9mm, 9mm mags will not take 38 super.

It is a fantastic pistol, and you get to own a light weight 1911 commander that shoots cheap. The 38 super is a fantastic cartridge. I have shot some of the corbon self defense rounds through it, which far exceed the energy of most .45acp comparable loads. The hot 38 super is equivalent to 9mm +P+, and just bellow .357 sig, yet it still has less recoil (subjective) then the .45 commanders I have shot.

I am open to trades with cash. The barrels and bushings will not be separated. 

Meeting in public, have CCW, be willing to fill out Washington State pistol transfer form. 

If you do not meet the criteria, or have a trade, or want to negotiate the price, please contact me. I am rather firm on the value, as I know what these go for and how much barrels are, but it does not hurt.

title: Want To Buy:  Good deals happen
postcontent:
There are lots of complainers on here, so I just wanted to provide a little bit of positive to offset the negative.  I realize this will generate hate mail and be flagged away, but let this be encouragement to those who still appreciate firearms as an American tradition and hobby.

 In the last 2-ish years, I have sold or traded  probably 5 firearms through contacts on armslist.  I have also bought just as many, plus a few more.  Every gun I have sold has been at a better than fair market price tag, because I don't own a gun shop and this isn't how I make my living.  Why would I expect to sell used firearms for more than I paid an actual dealer?  Nonsense.  The obvious exceptions are the ones I bought new for $80... 40 years ago.

I believe what comes around goes around.  And to this end, every single firearm I have purchased off this site has also been at a fair market value.  It's not magic or hocus pocus or karma.  That's the way the world turns people.  Stop trying to screw one another over, it will bite you back.

I hope this is an encouragement to those who are frustrated with the way this site is changing.  Don't abandon ship, there are still good people out there who enjoy firearms for what they are, not how much money they can make.
